                <note rend="inline" type="source">Paris Peace Conf. 181.9202/175: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">General <persName type="from">Bandholtz</persName> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Commission to Negotiate Peace</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Budapest</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-10-06">October 6,
                            1919</date>.<lb/>[Received October 6—9:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>125. At a conference between Admiral Troubridge, and the French Generals Graziani
                    and Franchet d’Esperey last Saturday at Szegedin <pb facs="0748" n="698"
                        xml:id="pg_698"/> which was called by the last named the Admiral recommended
                    that Hungarian peace delegates to be approved by the Interallied Military
                    Mission be sent to Paris without delay and it is understood such recommendation
                    was telegraphed M. Clemenceau. Coincident with the practical stoppage by the
                    rain of animal-drawn transport the Danube is usually closed to navigation. I
                    understand that bad weather is certain to begin about November 1st. I cannot too
                    strongly present the necessity for the immediate return of Hungarian rolling
                    stock and the withdrawal of the Roumanians.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bandholtz</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
